<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-689-438  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 689 438.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  August 7 1989 v3 n32 p10(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FBI expands crime reporting system. (automation and expansion ofthe Federal Bureau of Investigation's National Incident-BasedReporting System)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rivenbark, Leigh.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) expands its crimereports program to include details of almost every crime committedin the US.andP;  The automated version of the National Incident-BasedReporting System (NIBRS) will increase the volume of data gatheredfrom 1.5 million to 50 million reports per year.andP;  The states, 41of whom are enrolled in the current Uniform Crime Reports (UCR)program, will send even more detailed reports on each criminalincident.andP;  The current program employs Software AG's DBMS Adabasedata base management system software running on an Amdahl Corp5980 mainframe computer to create data files from tapes sent bythe states.andP;  The upgraded program will utilize a standard dataentry guide and a list of 52 data elements.andP;  Since states utilizea variety of hardware platforms running different types ofsoftware, the FBI expects the conversion to take from six to 10years.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Amdahl 5890 (Mainframe computer) (usage)DBMS Adabase (Data base management system) (usage).andO;Topic:     United States. Federal Bureau of InvestigationLaw EnforcementData Base Management SystemsInformation Storage and RetrievalGoals and ObjectivesAutomation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>